You are helping build a scientific Python repository for extracting ornithological observations from handwritten diaries.

General rules:
- Use type hints.
- Use Pydantic for data models.
- Prefer pure functions.
- Keep provenance metadata.
- Do not discard uncertainty.
- Never overwrite raw data.
- All LLM prompts must be versioned.
- All LLM responses must be cached.
- All extracted observations must link back to source volume, page, region and text span.
- Darwin Core export must exclude published literature observations unless explicitly configured otherwise.
- Add tests for all schema transformations.

Important requirements:
- Every result must preserve provenance: volume, page, side, region, text span, model, prompt version and confidence.
- Do not overwrite raw images.
- Use versioned prompts from the prompts directory.
- Use structured JSON outputs for LLM responses.
- Use Darwin Core terms where applicable.
- Exclude observations from published literature from the main DwC-A export.

Changelog:
- Update CHANGELOG.md under [Unreleased] for every meaningful change (features, fixes, breaking changes, removals).
- Use Keep a Changelog section headers: Added, Changed, Deprecated, Removed, Fixed, Security.
- Write changelog entries in German; keep section headers in English.
- Move entries from [Unreleased] to a versioned section only when releasing a new version.

Git:
- Never push to the remote repository unless the user explicitly asks.
- The user pushes commits themselves; do not offer or run `git push` proactively.
